ssification-reason "Post-hoc: zero sorry with substantive declarations", :output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (cycles, transpositions, S₅, and the subgroup G are named explicitly in both artifacts) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target assumes only “G contains a 5-cycle and a transposition” and *concludes* G = ⊤) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the statements stand on their own as precise group-theoretic claims) · notes: helper lemma isolates the standard fact that adjacent transpositions generate S₅, which is exactly what the informal argument will need.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Show that any subgroup of S₅ containing a 5-cycle and a transposition must contain all adjacent transpositions and hence equals the whole symmetric group.\"\n :terms [{:name \"5-cycle\"\n          :meaning \"A permutation whose cycle decomposition is a single cycle of length 5.\"\n          :needed-because \"Conjugating by this element lets us move indices around and forces transitivity.\"}\n         {:name \"transposition\"\n          :meaning \"A 2-cycle (i j) that swaps two letters and fixes the rest.\"\n          :needed-because \"Once we have one transposition we can conjugate it to obtain many others.\"}\n         {:name \"adjacent transpositions generate S₅\"\n          :meaning \"The set {(1 2),(2 3),(3 4),(4 5)} generates the full symmetric group.\"\n          :needed-because \"Our goal is to show these particular transpositions lie in G, forcing G=S₅.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"cycle_action.transitive\"\n             :informal-dependency \"A 5-cycle acts transitively on {1,…,5}, so any subgroup containing it is transitive.\"\n             :why-this-now \"Transitivity lets us relocate the given transposition via conjugation.\"\n             :lean-target \"∃ (σ : S_5), IsCycle σ ∧ orderOf σ = 5 ∧ σ ∈ G → ActingTransitively G\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib already shows cycles act transitively.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"conjh_transposition\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Use powers of the 5-cycle to conjugate the given transposition and obtain all translates (i i+1).\"\n             :why-this-now \"Generates the needed adjacent transpositions from a single 2-cycle.\"\n             :lean-target \"∀ i, (τ : S_5) transposition → σ^i τ σ^{-i} ∈ G\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Conjugation lemmas for permutations exist; will need a short calculation.\"}\n            {:id :s3\n             :formal-dependency \"adjacent_transpositions_generate\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Since the four adjacent transpositions lie in G, they generate S₅, hence G=S₅.\"\n             :why-this-now \"Closes the argument by appealing to the standard generating set.\"\n             :lean-target \"Subgroup.closure {adjacent transpositions} = ⊤\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib contains the fact that simple transpositions generate S_n.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"If a subgroup of S₅ contains a 5-cycle and a transposition, then it equals S₅.\"\n             :formal-name \"five_cycle_transposition_generate\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ (G : Subgroup (Equiv.Perm (Fin 5)))\n    {σ τ : Equiv.Perm (Fin 5)}, IsCycle σ ∧ orderOf σ = 5 ∧ σ ∈ G →\n    (τ.IsTransposition ∧ τ ∈ G) → G = ⊤\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Exactly the statement of the problem, expressed in terms of subgroups of S₅.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"five_cycle_transposition_generate\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ (G : Subgroup (Equiv.Perm (Fin 5))) … → G = ⊤\"\n              :informal-clause \"Certifies the main claim that possessing a 5-cycle and any transposition forces the whole symmetric group.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"adjacent_transpositions_generate\"\n              :formal-statement \"Subgroup.closure { (Equiv.swap 0 1), (Equiv.swap 1 2), (Equiv.swap 2 3), (Equiv.swap 3 4) } = ⊤\"\n              :informal-clause \"Used to deduce that once the four adjacent transpositions lie in G, we must have G=S₅.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** There are several proper subgroups of `S₅` that contain 5-cycles—the dihedral group `D₁₀`, the order‑20 Frobenius group, even `A₅`. It’s tempting to think “5-cycle + something of order 2 ⇒ S₅,” but unless the order‑2 element really is a transposition (fixing three points) you can sit strictly inside one of those subgroups. The mental pitfall is not checking how the 2-cycle interacts with the 5-cycle.\n\n**Key insight.** Conjugate everything until you have the canonical pair `(1 2 3 4 5)` and a transposition `(1 i)`. There are only two essential distances between 1 and i modulo 5: adjacent (difference ±1) and skipping one element (difference ±2). In the adjacent case the pair is already the standard generating set of `S₅`; in the skipping case the word `(σ τ)^3` *is* an adjacent transposition. Once a single adjacent transposition is available, conjugating by powers of the 5-cycle gives all of them, and those generate the whole symmetric group.\n\n**Complete proof.**\n\n1. Let `σ` be a 5-cycle in `G`. Conjugating inside `G` allows us to assume `σ = (1 2 3 4 5)` and the transposition is `τ = (1 i)` for some `i`.\n2. If `i = 2` or `i = 5`, then `τ` is already an adjacent transposition. Conjugating by powers of `σ` produces `(2 3)`, `(3 4)`, `(4 5)`, so all adjacent transpositions lie in `G`. Those generate `S₅`, so `G = S₅`.\n3. If `i = 3` (the case `i = 4` is symmetric), compute `σ τ = (1 4 5)(2 3)`. The factors commute, hence `(σ τ)^3 = (2 3)` lies in `G`. Conjugating by powers of `σ` now produces `(1 2)`, `(3 4)`, `(4 5)` as before, reducing to the previous case.\n4. Thus in all cases `G` contains the 5-cycle and all adjacent transpositions, forcing `G = S₅`.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.** File `ApmCanaries/Frames/B96J01/Apm_v2_b96J01_1775006550462/Main.lean` contains\n\n```lean\nlemma five_cycle_transposition_generate\n  (G : Subgroup (Equiv.Perm (Fin 5))) {σ τ}\n  (hσ_cycle : IsCycle σ) (hσ_ord : orderOf σ = 5) (hσ_mem : σ ∈ G)\n  (hτ_swap : IsSwap τ) (hτ_mem : τ ∈ G) :\n  G = ⊤\n```\n\nand the convenience wrapper `subgroup_eq_top_of_fiveCycle_and_swap`. The proof uses Mathlib’s `closure_prime_cycle_swap`, which states that on a set of prime cardinality, any prime cycle together with any transposition generates the full symmetric group. Since `σ` and `τ` lie in `G`, the closure of `{σ, τ}` sits inside `G`, but the lemma shows that closure is `⊤`, so `G = ⊤`. The build `lake build` succeeds (only the unrelated pre-existing warnings reappear).\n\n**What connects.**\n\n1. **Prime-degree permutation groups.** The strategy generalizes: if `G ≤ S_p` (p prime) contains a p-cycle and any odd permutation, then `G` is either `A_p` or `S_p`; a true transposition forces `S_p`.\n2. **Generators of `S_n`.** Remember that `(1 2 … n)` and `(1 2)` generate `S_n`; once you can spot adjacent transpositions you can generate everything.\n3. **Closure lemmas.** Mathlib’s `closure_prime_cycle_swap` is useful beyond degree 5—it gives a ready-made Lean proof whenever you encounter “prime cycle + swap” in any finite symmetric group.\n4. **Conjugation tricks.** Conjugating to normal forms drastically simplifies permutation arguments; it’s the standard move whenever “contains a cycle of this type” appears.\n5. **Dihedral/Frobenius subgroups.** When facing similar problems, check whether the given elements could sit inside the dihedral normalizer of a cycle or the affine group on `ℤ/pℤ`; spotting the extra transposition rules those out instantly.\n\nThis finishes the problem in both prose and Lean, and all frame artefacts have been populated accordingly.", :frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B96J01/Apm_v2_b96J01_1775006550462", :frame/id "apm-v2-b96J01-1775006550462", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T01:22:30.484774Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.B96J01.Apm_v2_b96J01_1775006550462", :proof/problem-id "b96J01", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b96J01/apm-v2-b96J01-1775006550462", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b96J01/apm-v2-b96J01-1775006550462/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b96J01/apm-v2-b96J01-1775006550462/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b96J01/apm-v2-b96J01-1775006550462/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b96J01/apm-v2-b96J01-1775006550462/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b96J01/apm-v2-b96J01-1775006550462/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b96J01/apm-v2-b96J01-1775006550462/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B96J01/Apm_v2_b96J01_1775006550462/Main.lean", :lean-scratch "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B96J01/Apm_v2_b96J01_1775006550462/Scratch.lean"}}, :artifacts ["/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B96J01/Apm_v2_b96J01_1775006550462/Main.lean" "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B96J01/Apm_v2_b96J01_1775006550462/Scratch.lean"], :problem-id "apm-b96J01", :reclassified-at "2026-04-01T11:58:15.790233418Z", :elapsed-ms 298815}